# Project Configuration

## Technology Stack

| Layer | Choice |
|---|---|
| UI | React 19 |
| State | Zustand 5 (global) + TanStack Query 5 (server) |
| Language | TypeScript 6.0 strict |
| Bundler | Vite 8 (Rolldown + Oxc — official `vite` package) |
| Styling | Tailwind CSS **v4** (CSS-based config — no tailwind.config.ts) |
| Components | shadcn/ui (new-york style) |
| Routing | React Router v7 |
| Forms | react-hook-form v7 + zod v4 |
| i18n | i18next 26 + react-i18next 17 |
| Testing | Vitest 4 + Testing Library |

## Tailwind v4 (CRITICAL)

**There is no `tailwind.config.ts`.** All config in `src/index.css`:

```css
@import "tailwindcss";
@import "tw-animate-css";
@custom-variant dark (&:where(.dark, .dark *));

@theme inline {
  --color-primary: hsl(var(--primary));
  /* ... all tokens here */
}

:root { --primary: 221.2 83.2% 53.3%; }
.dark { --primary: 217.2 91.2% 59.8%; }
```

- Dark mode via `.dark` class (NOT `darkMode: 'class'` in JS config — that file doesn't exist).
- Animations via `tw-animate-css` package (CSS import, not a PostCSS plugin).
- `@tailwindcss/vite` handles compilation — do NOT add tailwindcss to PostCSS.
- Adding new color token: add HSL value to `:root`, map in `@theme inline`.

## i18n

- Translations in `public/locales/{lng}/{ns}.json`
- Namespaces: `common` (always loaded), `errors` (always loaded), page-specific (lazy), feature-specific (lazy on demand)
- Language detection: `localStorage` → browser → fallback `'en'`
- HMR: auto-reload translations in dev when files in `public/locales/` change
- No hardcoded user-visible strings — always use `t('key')`.

```typescript
const { t } = useTranslation(['common', 'home']);
return <h1>{t('home:title')}</h1>;
```

## Accessibility

- Semantic HTML first: prefer `<button>`, `<nav>`, `<main>` over `<div role="...">`.
- ARIA only where semantic HTML is insufficient.
- Loading states: `role="status"` + `aria-live="polite"`.
- Error states: `role="alert"` + `aria-live="assertive"`.
- Keyboard navigation: all interactive elements must be keyboard-reachable.
- shadcn/ui components include accessibility by default — don't override without reason.

## Path Aliases

`@/` maps to `src/`. **Only use `@/` aliases — never relative `../../`.**

```typescript
import { useUserStore } from '@/store/user/userStore';
import { cn } from '@/lib/utils';
import { Button } from '@/components/ui/button';
```

## UI Quality — avoid the AI aesthetic

AI-generated UI has recognizable tells. For any UI work reject the default in favour of the tokens in `src/index.css`:

- **Palette**: brand is `--primary` = **Google Blue** (`221.2 83.2% 53.3%` light / `217.2 91.2% 59.8%` dark). Never reach for the AI-default purple/indigo. Use the semantic tokens (`primary`, `secondary`, `muted`, `accent`, `destructive`) — no raw hex / `bg-violet-500`.
- **No new ad-hoc colors**: a color needs a token. Add HSL to `:root` + `.dark`, map in `@theme inline` (see Tailwind v4 above) — don't sprinkle one-off literals.
- **Gradients**: none are defined in the theme — keep surfaces flat. No decorative `bg-gradient-to-*` unless a real design calls for it.
- **Radius**: respect the scale — `--radius: 0.5rem` drives `rounded-sm`/`rounded-md`/`rounded-lg` (`--radius-sm/md/lg`). Vary radius by hierarchy; don't slap `rounded-2xl`/`rounded-full` on everything.
- **Shadows**: the theme ships no custom elevation tokens — depth is subtle. Avoid shadow-heavy cards (`shadow-2xl`); shadcn/ui new-york defaults are the ceiling unless specified.
- **Spacing**: use the Tailwind scale, not uniform oversized padding (`p-8`/`gap-12` everywhere). Let hierarchy set the rhythm.
- **Layout**: content-first and priority-driven over a generic template hero + uniform stock card grid. LCP-priority element first (see performance rules).
- **Copy**: realistic content via `t()` keys, never lorem-ipsum — real strings reveal real wrapping / overflow / length (and keep i18n honest).
- **Dark mode**: every surface must read in both themes — verify against `.dark` tokens, don't hardcode a light-only color.
- **Charts**: use `--chart-1`…`--chart-5`, not arbitrary picked colors.
- **Baseline only**: prefer Baseline "Widely available" Web APIs; do not introduce "Newly available" ones (e.g. `scheduler.yield()`) without a fallback.

## Interaction & base-layer states (binding)

- **States must be PERCEPTIBLY DISTINCT, not merely present.** A hover / active / focus / selection colour must not resolve to ≈ the element's own default or background colour — verify it is VISIBLE. Failure modes seen in the wild: a base link colour equal to its `hover:` colour (zero visible hover — only the cursor changes); a `::selection` highlight built on a near-background token (invisible selection). Chrome/nav links default to a neutral (`text-muted-foreground`) so the `hover:text-primary` shift shows.
- **Compound states must stay COHERENT.** When two states co-occur (focus+invalid, hover+selected, disabled+focus) they must not visually fight — the more urgent state owns the shared channel (e.g. an invalid field recolours its focus ring, `aria-invalid:focus-visible:ring-destructive`, so focused+invalid reads as one error state; disabled cancels hover). Check state PAIRS, not just singles.
- **Base-layer globals** (`::selection`, base links, `:focus-visible`) must be perceptibly distinct AND must NOT be built on quiet near-background tokens (`--muted`, or an `--accent` that is a slate-3-style near-background neutral). System feedback (selection, focus ring) is built on `--primary` / `--ring`, never the quiet hover token. If you define `::selection`, use `background-color: hsl(var(--primary)); color: hsl(var(--primary-foreground));` — a quiet token renders the highlight invisible.

## PWA — load-bearing config (CRITICAL — DO NOT TOUCH casually)

This is a PWA template. The service-worker and manifest wiring is fragile and several settings are **decided once / destructive to change**. Full reference + threat model: `.cursor/brain/PWA.md`; danger zones: `.cursor/brain/SKELETONS.md`. NEVER change any of the following without explicit approval (Approval Law):

- **`registerType: 'prompt'` is decided ONCE.** It lives in `vite.config.ts` (`VitePWA(...)`). **NEVER** flip `'prompt'` → `'autoUpdate'` (or back) post-deploy — it is destructive: the toast/no-toast contract leaks into production caches, and `autoUpdate` silently force-reloads tabs and **destroys mid-session form state** (vite-pwa #228/#438). The template defaults to `'prompt'` for that reason.
- **Ship BOTH `apple-mobile-web-app-capable` AND `mobile-web-app-capable` meta tags** in `index.html` (lines 25–26). MDN flags `apple-*` as deprecated, but iOS Safari **still** silently breaks home-screen splash screens without it. **NEVER** "clean up" the apparent duplicate (next.js #70272 / #74524).
- **MSW × Workbox precache order is load-bearing.** In `vite.config.ts`, `removeMswPlugin()` MUST stay registered **before** `VitePWA(...)` so its `closeBundle` deletes `dist/mockServiceWorker.js` before the precache scan finalizes. **Reordering them ships MSW's worker as a dead precache entry → 404 storm on every install.** `workbox.globIgnores` is defence-in-depth; `scripts/check-pwa.mjs` fails the build if `dist/sw.js` references `mockServiceWorker.js` — NEVER bypass it.
- **Two service workers never coexist by design**: `public/mockServiceWorker.js` (MSW, DEV-only, gated by `import.meta.env.DEV` in `src/main.tsx`) and `dist/sw.js` (vite-plugin-pwa, PROD-only, `devOptions.enabled: false`). Do not enable PWA in dev or register MSW in prod.
